The paper deals with the decidability and undecidability of mean-payoff games on timed automata, which involves both logic and automata theory. Therefore, cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves formal languages and automata, which suggests cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) as the second likely sub-category. The paper also uses dynamic programming techniques, which are commonly used in cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Additionally, the paper involves optimization and decision-making, which are relevant to cs.PL (Programming Languages) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence).
